hook.real_world_problem:
From Topic 5.5, you wrote Comparators like this:

```java
Collections.sort(products, new Comparator<Product>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Product a, Product b) {
        return Double.compare(a.getPrice(), b.getPrice());
    }
});
```

5 lines. For something that could be expressed as: *'compare two products by price.'*

With a lambda:

```java
Collections.sort(products, (a, b) -> Double.compare(a.getPrice(), b.getPrice()));
```

One line. Same logic. No boilerplate.

Before Java 8, every Comparator, every Runnable, every ActionListener required a full anonymous class. Java 8 introduced lambdas — a concise way to pass a FUNCTION as a value. The anonymous class boilerplate collapses to an arrow `->` and the actual logic.

But lambdas aren't just syntactic sugar. They're a fundamental shift: **treating functions as values** — passing them around, storing them in variables, returning them from methods. This unlocks an entire functional programming paradigm in Java. Today you learn the syntax. Starting Topic 8.3, you use them to transform data in powerful ways.

concept_explanation.functional_interface:
A **functional interface** is an interface with exactly one abstract method:

```java
// These are all functional interfaces:
@FunctionalInterface
interface Comparator<T> { int compare(T a, T b); }  // one abstract method

@FunctionalInterface
interface Runnable { void run(); }  // one abstract method

@FunctionalInterface
interface Predicate<T> { boolean test(T t); }  // one abstract method
```

`@FunctionalInterface` is an optional annotation — it tells the compiler to enforce that there's only one abstract method. You can omit it, but it's good documentation.

**Why does this matter?** When Java sees a lambda being passed where a functional interface is expected, it uses the lambda as the implementation of that single abstract method:

```java
Comparator<String> byLength = (a, b) -> Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
// Java knows: Comparator has one method: compare(T a, T b)
// The lambda IS that compare method
```

concept_explanation.syntax_forms:
**Lambda syntax — three forms:**

**Form 1: Expression lambda** (most common — single expression that IS the return value)
```java
(int x) -> x * 2          // returns x * 2
(String s) -> s.length()  // returns length
(a, b) -> a + b           // type inferred, returns sum
```

**Form 2: Block lambda** (when you need multiple statements — explicit return required)
```java
(String s) -> {
    String upper = s.toUpperCase();
    return upper + "!";
}

(int a, int b) -> {
    if (a > b) return a;
    return b;
}
```

**Form 3: No parameters**
```java
() -> System.out.println("hello")
() -> 42  // returns 42
() -> Math.random()
```

**Type inference**: Java infers parameter types from the functional interface context:
```java
Comparator<String> byLen = (a, b) -> Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
//                          ↑ ↑ — Java knows these are Strings from Comparator<String>

// Optional: explicit types (only when inference is ambiguous):
Comparator<String> byLen = (String a, String b) -> Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
```

**Single parameter — parentheses optional**:
```java
(s) -> s.toUpperCase()  // OK
s -> s.toUpperCase()    // also OK — parens optional for single param
```

concept_explanation.lambda_vs_anonymous:
**Lambda vs anonymous class — they're equivalent, lambda is cleaner:**

```java
// Anonymous class (old way):
Comparator<String> byLen = new Comparator<String>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(String a, String b) {
        return Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
    }
};

// Lambda (new way — same effect):
Comparator<String> byLen = (a, b) -> Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
```

Lambda is:
- Shorter (1 line vs 5)
- No `@Override`, no return type, no `new Comparator<>(){}` noise
- Just the logic that matters

**One important difference**: lambdas don't create a new `this` reference. Inside an anonymous class, `this` refers to the anonymous class instance. Inside a lambda, `this` refers to the enclosing class. This rarely matters but can come up.

concept_explanation.lambdas_with_sort:
**Lambda with sort — the most common use:**

```java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Priya", "Aisha", "Raj");

// Sort alphabetically
names.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));

// Sort by length ascending
names.sort((a, b) -> Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length()));

// Sort by length descending
names.sort((a, b) -> Integer.compare(b.length(), a.length()));

// Multi-criteria: length asc, then alpha for ties
names.sort((a, b) -> {
    int cmp = Integer.compare(a.length(), b.length());
    return cmp != 0 ? cmp : a.compareTo(b);
});

// Even shorter with Comparator factory methods:
names.sort(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length));
names.sort(Comparator.comparing(s -> s));
```

concept_explanation.lambdas_with_foreach:
**Lambda with forEach — iterate and act:**

```java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj", "Priya");

// Print each
names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));

// Transform and print
names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name.toUpperCase()));

// With Map
Map<String, Integer> scores = new HashMap<>();
scores.put("Aisha", 95);
scores.put("Raj", 87);
scores.forEach((name, score) -> 
    System.out.println(name + ": " + score));
```

`forEach` takes a `Consumer<T>` — a functional interface with one method `accept(T t)`. The lambda IS the accept implementation.

`Map.forEach` takes a `BiConsumer<K, V>` — two parameters, no return.

concept_explanation.method_references_preview:
**Method references** — even shorter lambda syntax (when the lambda just calls one method):

```java
// Lambda calling a method:
names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));
// Method reference — same thing:
names.forEach(System.out::println);

// Lambda calling instance method on the parameter:
names.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
// Method reference:
names.sort(String::compareTo);

// Lambda calling static method:
List<String> strings = Arrays.asList("1", "2", "3");
strings.stream().map(s -> Integer.parseInt(s))...
// Method reference:
strings.stream().map(Integer::parseInt)...
```

`ClassName::methodName` or `object::methodName`. We'll use these throughout Module 8. For now, recognize the pattern: if the lambda just calls one method, you can shorten it to a method reference.

